{
  "At equilibrium, which statement is true about a reversible reaction?": "",
  "All reactants have been converted to products": "",
  "The reaction has stopped completely": "",
  "Both forward and reverse reactions occur at equal rates": "",
  "Only forward reaction occurs": "",
  "At equilibrium, both forward and reverse reactions continue at equal rates. Concentrations remain constant but the system is dynamic, not static.": "",
  "For the reaction N₂(g) + 3H₂(g) ⇌ 2NH₃(g), what is the equilibrium expression?": "",
  "Keq = 2[NH₃] / ([N₂] + 3[H₂])": "",
  "Keq = [N₂][H₂]³ / [NH₃]²": "",
  "Keq = [NH₃]² / ([N₂][H₂]³)": "",
  "Keq = [NH₃] / ([N₂][H₂])": "",
  "The equilibrium expression has products over reactants, each raised to their stoichiometric coefficient: Keq = [NH₃]² / ([N₂][H₂]³).": "",
  "If K >> 1 for a reaction at equilibrium, which statement is correct?": "",
  "The reaction does not reach equilibrium": "",
  "Reactants are favored": "",
  "Equal amounts of reactants and products exist": "",
  "Products are favored": "",
  "When K >> 1, the numerator (products) is much larger than the denominator (reactants), meaning the equilibrium position strongly favors product formation.": "",
  "Which of the following does NOT affect the value of Keq?": "",
  "Reversing the reaction": "",
  "A catalyst": "",
  "Temperature": "",
  "Changing the balanced equation": "",
  "A catalyst speeds up both forward and reverse reactions equally, reaching equilibrium faster without changing the equilibrium constant. Only temperature changes the value of K.": "",
  "Pure solids and pure liquids are excluded from the equilibrium expression because:": "",
  "They have no effect on equilibrium": "",
  "Their concentrations (activities) are constant and equal to 1": "",
  "They don't participate in the reaction": "",
  "They are always in excess": "",
  "Pure solids and liquids have constant concentrations regardless of amount present. Their activities are defined as 1 and are incorporated into the equilibrium constant itself.": "",
  "If Q < K for a reaction, in which direction will the reaction shift?": "",
  "No shift; the system is at equilibrium": "",
  "Toward reactants (reverse)": "",
  "The reaction stops": "",
  "Toward products (forward)": "",
  "When Q < K, there are relatively more reactants than at equilibrium. The system shifts forward (toward products) until Q = K and equilibrium is reestablished.": "",
  "For the equilibrium 2SO₂(g) + O₂(g) ⇌ 2SO₃(g), if the volume is decreased at constant temperature, which direction does equilibrium shift?": "",
  "Cannot be determined": "",
  "No shift": "",
  "Toward reactants (more moles of gas)": "",
  "Toward products (fewer moles of gas)": "",
  "Decreasing volume increases pressure. The system shifts toward the side with fewer moles of gas to reduce pressure. Reactants have 3 moles of gas, products have 2, so the shift is toward products.": "",
  "What is the relationship between Kp and Kc?": "",
  "Kp = Kc / RT, even when conditions shift significantly": "",
  "Kp = Kc always, which is a common assumption in the field": "",
  "Kp = Kc(RT)^Δn where Δn = moles gaseous products - moles gaseous reactants": "",
  "They are unrelated quantities, especially during periods": "",
  "Kp and Kc are related by Kp = Kc(RT)^Δn. When Δn = 0 (equal moles of gas on both sides), Kp = Kc.": "",
  "If the equilibrium constant for A → B is K₁, what is the equilibrium constant for 2A → 2B?": "",
  "K₁/2": "",
  "K₁": "",
  "K₁²": "",
  "2K₁": "",
  "When a balanced equation is multiplied by a factor n, the new equilibrium constant is the original K raised to the nth power. Multiplying by 2 gives K₁².": "",
  "At 25°C, the Ksp of AgCl is 1.8 × 10⁻¹⁰. What is the molar solubility of AgCl?": "",
  "3.2 × 10⁻² M": "",
  "1.8 × 10⁻¹⁰ M": "",
  "1.3 × 10⁻⁵ M": "",
  "9.0 × 10⁻⁶ M": "",
  "AgCl → Ag⁺ + Cl⁻. Ksp = s² where s is molar solubility. s = √(1.8 × 10⁻¹⁰) = 1.3 × 10⁻⁵ M.": "",
  "What is 'chemical equilibrium'?": "",
  "A dynamic state where the rates of the forward and reverse reactions are equal, resulting in constant concentrations of reactants and products": "",
  "A state where all reactants have been consumed": "",
  "A state that can only be achieved in closed systems at 0°C": "",
  "A state where the reaction has stopped and no changes occur": "",
  "Chemical equilibrium is dynamic: reactions continue in both directions at equal rates. Macroscopic properties (concentrations) remain constant, but molecular-level reactions never stop.": "",
  "What does 'equilibrium constant (K)' mean?": "",
  "The rate at which a reaction reaches equilibrium": "",
  "The total concentration of all species at equilibrium": "",
  "The time required for a reaction to reach equilibrium": "",
  "A ratio of product concentrations to reactant concentrations (each raised to stoichiometric powers) at equilibrium at a given temperature": "",
  "The equilibrium constant K is the ratio of product concentrations to reactant concentrations at equilibrium, each raised to the power of its stoichiometric coefficient. K depends only on temperature.": "",
  "What is the 'reaction quotient (Q)'?": "",
  "The equilibrium constant at standard conditions": "",
  "The rate of the forward reaction divided by the rate of the reverse reaction": "",
  "The number of moles of product formed per mole of reactant consumed": "",
  "The same expression as K but calculated using current (non-equilibrium) concentrations to predict the direction of shift": "",
  "Q has the same mathematical form as K but uses current concentrations rather than equilibrium concentrations. Comparing Q to K predicts whether a reaction will shift forward (Q < K) or reverse (Q > K).": "",
  "What does 'Le Chatelier's Principle' state?": "",
  "Equilibrium constants change when pressure is applied": "",
  "Catalysts change the position of equilibrium": "",
  "When a system at equilibrium is disturbed, it shifts to partially counteract the change and establish a new equilibrium": "",
  "All reactions eventually reach equilibrium": "",
  "Le Chatelier's Principle states that if a stress (concentration change, pressure change, or temperature change) is applied to a system at equilibrium, the system shifts to partially offset that stress.": "",
  "What is 'Ksp' (solubility product constant)?": "",
  "The total amount of solute that dissolves in a given volume, even when conditions shift significantly": "",
  "The equilibrium constant for the dissolution of a sparingly soluble ionic compound, equal to the product of ion concentrations raised to stoichiometric powers": "",
  "The ratio of dissolved to undissolved solute, since the prevailing theory about constant would support this particular interpretation": "",
  "The rate constant for dissolution reactions because conventional analysis of constant suggests this would be the expected result": "",
  "Ksp is the equilibrium constant specifically for the dissolution of a sparingly soluble salt. For AgCl: Ksp = [Ag⁺][Cl⁻]. A larger Ksp indicates greater solubility.": "",
  "What does 'dynamic equilibrium' mean?": "",
  "Forward and reverse processes continue at equal rates even though macroscopic properties remain constant": "",
  "The system has reached maximum entropy": "",
  "The system is changing rapidly": "",
  "Only the forward reaction is occurring": "",
  "'Dynamic' means the reactions are still occurring (molecules are constantly reacting), while 'equilibrium' means the net concentrations don't change because the forward and reverse rates are equal.": "",
  "What is meant by 'homogeneous equilibrium'?": "",
  "An equilibrium where all reactants and products are in the same phase": "",
  "An equilibrium with only one reactant": "",
  "An equilibrium that only involves gases": "",
  "An equilibrium involving reactants and products in different phases": "",
  "Homogeneous equilibrium occurs when all species are in the same phase (e.g., all gases or all in aqueous solution). Heterogeneous equilibrium involves species in different phases.": "",
  "What does 'ICE table' stand for in equilibrium calculations?": "",
  "Initial, Change, Equilibrium - a systematic method to calculate equilibrium concentrations": "",
  "Ion Concentration Expression, especially during periods of significant change": "",
  "Ionic, Covalent, Equilibrium under most circumstances involving concentrations": "",
  "Internal Combustion Energy under most circumstances involving concentrations": "",
  "An ICE table organizes the Initial concentrations, the Change in concentrations (using stoichiometry), and the Equilibrium concentrations. It is the standard method for solving equilibrium problems.": "",
  "What is 'heterogeneous equilibrium'?": "",
  "An equilibrium where all species are gases": "",
  "An equilibrium that never reaches a stable state": "",
  "An equilibrium between two different reactions": "",
  "Heterogeneous equilibrium involves species in multiple phases. For example, CaCO₃(s) ⇌ CaO(s) + CO₂(g) involves solids and a gas. Pure solids and liquids are omitted from the K expression.": "",
  "What does 'common ion effect' mean?": "",
  "Two different salts always have the same solubility": "",
  "Increasing temperature always increases solubility": "",
  "Adding more solvent increases solubility": "",
  "The decrease in solubility of a sparingly soluble salt when a common ion is added, shifting the equilibrium toward the undissolved solid": "",
  "The common ion effect occurs when an ion already present in solution decreases the solubility of a salt that contains that same ion, by shifting the dissolution equilibrium toward the solid (Le Chatelier's principle).": "",
  "A soda bottling plant carbonates water by dissolving CO₂ under high pressure. The equilibrium CO₂(g) ⇌ CO₂(aq) governs the process. When a consumer opens the bottle, the pressure drops suddenly. Using Le Chatelier's principle, explain why the soda fizzes.": "",
  "Opening the bottle adds oxygen, which reacts with CO₂": "",
  "Reducing the pressure of CO₂ gas above the liquid shifts equilibrium toward the gas phase, causing dissolved CO₂ to escape as bubbles": "",
  "The temperature change from the refrigerator causes CO₂ to escape": "",
  "The common ion effect forces CO₂ out of solution": "",
  "When the bottle is opened, the partial pressure of CO₂ above the liquid decreases. By Le Chatelier's principle, the equilibrium shifts to produce more gas-phase CO₂, causing dissolved CO₂ to come out of solution as bubbles.": "",
  "A chemical engineer at a fertilizer plant uses the Haber process: N₂(g) + 3H₂(g) ⇌ 2NH₃(g), ΔH = -92 kJ. She wants to maximize ammonia production. Which combination of conditions favors the highest equilibrium yield of NH₃?": "",
  "Low temperature and high pressure": "",
  "Low temperature and low pressure": "",
  "High temperature and high pressure": "",
  "High temperature and low pressure": "",
  "The reaction is exothermic (ΔH < 0), so low temperature favors products. The product side has fewer moles of gas (2 vs 4), so high pressure shifts equilibrium toward products. However, low temperature slows the rate, requiring a catalyst.": "",
  "A water treatment plant tests whether BaSO₄ will precipitate when mixing waste streams. One stream has [Ba²⁺] = 0.010 M and the other has [SO₄²⁻] = 0.005 M. The Ksp of BaSO₄ is 1.1 × 10⁻¹⁰. After mixing (assuming volumes double), will a precipitate form?": "",
  "Cannot determine without temperature data": "",
  "No, because BaSO₄ is soluble": "",
  "Yes, because Q > Ksp after mixing": "",
  "No, because Q < Ksp": "",
  "After mixing equal volumes, concentrations halve: [Ba²⁺] = 0.005, [SO₄²⁻] = 0.0025. Q = (0.005)(0.0025) = 1.25 × 10⁻⁵, which is far greater than Ksp (1.1 × 10⁻¹⁰), so BaSO₄ precipitates.": "",
  "A biochemist studies hemoglobin-oxygen binding: Hb + 4O₂ ⇌ Hb(O₂)₄. In the lungs, the partial pressure of O₂ is high, and in the tissues it is low. How does this equilibrium explain oxygen transport?": "",
  "Hemoglobin binds CO₂ instead of O₂ in the tissues": "",
  "Temperature differences between lungs and tissues control oxygen binding": "",
  "Hemoglobin permanently binds oxygen and releases it only when it degrades": "",
  "High O₂ in the lungs shifts equilibrium toward Hb(O₂)₄ (loading), while low O₂ in tissues shifts it toward free Hb + O₂ (unloading)": "",
  "Le Chatelier's principle explains oxygen transport: high O₂ concentration in the lungs shifts equilibrium toward the bound form, while low O₂ in tissues shifts it toward release, enabling efficient O₂ delivery.": "",
  "A geologist studies limestone caves. Calcium carbonate dissolves via: CaCO₃(s) + CO₂(aq) + H₂O(l) ⇌ Ca²⁺(aq) + 2HCO₃⁻(aq). Rainwater absorbs CO₂ from the atmosphere and dissolves limestone underground. When the water drips into a cave and CO₂ escapes into the air, stalactites form. What equilibrium shift causes stalactite formation?": "",
  "Adding water shifts the equilibrium toward products": "",
  "Gravity pulls calcium ions downward to form stalactites": "",
  "Loss of CO₂ shifts equilibrium toward reactants, causing CaCO₃ to precipitate and form stalactites": "",
  "Increased temperature in the cave dissolves more CaCO₃": "",
  "When CO₂-rich water enters a cave, CO₂ escapes into the air (removing a reactant). This shifts the equilibrium to the left, causing CaCO₃ to precipitate. Over thousands of years, this builds stalactites and stalagmites.": "",
  "A pool maintenance worker adds calcium chloride to pool water to prevent etching of the plaster. The equilibrium is: CaCO₃(s) ⇌ Ca²⁺(aq) + CO₃²⁻(aq). How does adding CaCl₂ protect the plaster?": "",
  "CaCl₂ acts as a catalyst for the reverse reaction": "",
  "CaCl₂ reacts with CO₃²⁻ to form a protective coating": "",
  "Adding Ca²⁺ ions (common ion effect) shifts the equilibrium toward the solid CaCO₃, preventing dissolution of the plaster": "",
  "CaCl₂ increases the pH of the pool water": "",
  "Adding Ca²⁺ from CaCl₂ increases Q above Ksp (common ion effect). The equilibrium shifts left toward solid CaCO₃, preventing the plaster from dissolving and protecting the pool surface.": "",
  "A medical researcher is studying how carbon monoxide (CO) poisoning works. CO binds to hemoglobin 200 times more strongly than O₂: Hb + CO ⇌ HbCO (K is very large). Treatment involves placing the patient in a hyperbaric chamber with pure O₂ at high pressure. Why does this work?": "",
  "The extremely high concentration of O₂ shifts the Hb + O₂ ⇌ HbO₂ equilibrium far toward HbO₂, competitively displacing CO from hemoglobin": "",
  "Pressure physically squeezes CO off the hemoglobin in most scenarios involving strongly factors": "",
  "High-pressure O₂ chemically destroys CO molecules, even when conditions shift significantly": "",
  "High-pressure O₂ converts CO into CO₂ according to widely held views on this topic": "",
  "While CO binds 200x more strongly, flooding the system with enormous O₂ concentrations shifts the O₂-binding equilibrium strongly forward. By mass action, O₂ gradually displaces CO from hemoglobin binding sites.": "",
  "An industrial chemist notices that the Haber process reactor (N₂ + 3H₂ ⇌ 2NH₃) uses an iron catalyst and operates at 400-500°C despite the reaction being exothermic. She knows low temperature favors products. Why is high temperature used in practice?": "",
  "High temperature increases the equilibrium constant for this reaction": "",
  "Although high temperature decreases the yield, it is necessary to achieve a practical reaction rate; the catalyst helps but cannot make it fast enough at low temperature": "",
  "High temperature is needed to keep the gases in the gaseous phase": "",
  "The iron catalyst only works at high temperatures": "",
  "This is a classic equilibrium vs. kinetics trade-off. Low T favors products thermodynamically but the reaction would be too slow. Operating at 400-500°C with a catalyst provides a compromise between acceptable yield and practical rate.": "",
  "A kidney dialysis machine works by passing blood alongside a dialysis solution separated by a semipermeable membrane. Urea and other waste products are at higher concentration in the blood. Using equilibrium principles, why does urea move from the blood into the dialysis solution?": "",
  "The membrane actively pumps urea out of the blood": "",
  "Urea diffuses down its concentration gradient from blood to dialysate until equilibrium is approached, effectively removing waste from the blood": "",
  "Electrical charges in the membrane repel urea from the blood": "",
  "The dialysis solution contains enzymes that break down urea": "",
  "Urea moves from high concentration (blood) to low concentration (dialysate) by diffusion, driven toward equilibrium. Fresh dialysate is continuously supplied to maintain the concentration gradient, effectively removing waste.": "",
  "A farmer notices white deposits forming on the soil surface after irrigation with hard water. The water contains dissolved Ca(HCO₃)₂. As water evaporates at the surface, the equilibrium Ca(HCO₃)₂(aq) ⇌ CaCO₃(s) + H₂O(l) + CO₂(g) shifts. Which factors drive the formation of these deposits?": "",
  "Evaporation removes water and CO₂ escapes to the atmosphere, both shifting equilibrium toward CaCO₃ precipitation": "",
  "Bacteria in the soil convert bicarbonate to carbonate": "",
  "Addition of more water shifts equilibrium toward products": "",
  "Sunlight catalyzes the decomposition of calcium bicarbonate": "",
  "Evaporation removes water (a product) and CO₂ escapes into the atmosphere (removing another product). By Le Chatelier's principle, removing products shifts the equilibrium to the right, precipitating solid CaCO₃.": ""
}